Multi-Cell-Aware Opportunistic Random Access for Machine-Type Communications (Huifa Lin - 9 August, 2017)
In this paper, we propose a decentralized multi-cell-aware opportunistic random access (MA-ORA) protocol that achieves the optimal throughput scaling in an ultra-dense $K$-cell random access network with one access point (AP) and $N$ users in each cell, which is suited for machine-type communications. As a main result, it is proved that the aggregate throughput scales as $\frac{K}{e}(1-Îµ) \log (\textsf{snr} \log N)$ in a high signal-to-noise ratio (SNR) regime if $N$ scales faster than $\textsf{snr}^{\frac{K-1}{1-Î´}}$ for small constants $Îµ, Î´>0$
